    "content": "<70-74>\nBefore General Kawagishi and Other Generals, the Tokyo International Student Representative Takes an Oath, A Celebration Meeting for the Conscription System in the Imperial Capital\n\nThe other day, following the announcement of the conscription system, young men from the Peninsula [Korea] studying abroad in Tokyo gathered together to hold a gratitude and celebration meeting. On that day, many students burning with enthusiasm gathered. Furthermore, specially attending on the day were:\n\nKorea Scholarship Association (朝鮮獎學會) Director, Lieutenant General Kawagishi (川岸中將)\nPrisoner of War Information Bureau (浮虜情報局) Director, Lieutenant General Uemura (上村中將)\nArmy Preparatory Officer School (陸軍豫科士官學校) Head Instructor, Major General Makino (牧野少將), Major General Hasegawa (長谷川少將)\n\nThey were present. The following text is the fervent oath given by the student representative, Mr. Sin (申君), on that day.\n\nWe Hereby Swear\n\nTokyo, Nihon Daigaku (日本大學) Sin Ryonggyun (申龍均)\n\n**Summary**\n\nThis article reports on a meeting held in Tokyo by Korean students studying abroad to celebrate the implementation of the Japanese conscription system for Koreans in 1942. Several high-ranking Japanese military officials attended the event, where a student representative, Sin Ryonggyun from Nihon Daigaku, delivered a fervent oath on behalf of the students. The article highlights the enthusiastic participation of Korean students in celebrating a policy aimed at integrating them fully into the Japanese war effort. For historians, this piece is significant as it exemplifies the complex dynamics of collaboration and assimilation during the late colonial period. It showcases how some Korean elites or students publicly displayed loyalty and support (whether genuine or coerced) for Japanese imperial policies, providing valuable propaganda material for the Japanese regime.\n\n**Named Entities**\n\n川岸中將\tかわぎしちゅうじょう\tLieutenant General Kawagishi\n上村中將\tうえむらちゅうじょう\tLieutenant General Uemura\n牧野少將\tまきのしょうしょう\tMajor General Makino\n長谷川少將\tはせがわしょうしょう\tMajor General Hasegawa\n申君\tしんくん\tMr. Sin\n申龍均\t신룡균\tSin Ryonggyun\n東京\tとうきょう\tTokyo\n日本大學\tにほんだいがく\tNihon Daigaku\n半島\tはんとう\tPeninsula (Korea)\n帝都\tていと\tImperial Capital (Tokyo)\n朝鮮獎學會\tちょうせんしょうがくかい\tChōsen Shōgakkai (Korea Scholarship Association)\n浮虜情報局\tふりょじょうほうきょく\tFuryo Jōhōkyoku (Prisoner of War Information Bureau)\n陸軍豫科士官學校\tりくぐんよかしかんがっこう\tRikugun Yoka Shikan Gakkō (Army Preparatory Officer School)\n\n**Glossary**\n\n將星\tしょうせい\tGeneral(s), high-ranking military officer(s)\n留學生\tりゅうがくせい\tInternational student, student studying abroad\n誓ふ\tちかう\tTo swear, to take an oath (Classical/older form of 誓う)\n帝都\tていと\tImperial Capital (referring to Tokyo)\n徵兵制\tちょうへいせい\tConscription system, draft\n祝賀會\tしゅくがかい\tCelebration meeting\n遊學\tゆうがく\tStudying abroad\n半島\tはんとう\tPeninsula (used to refer to Korea)\n靑年\tせいねん\tYouth, young man\n相集り\tあいあつまり\tTo gather together (Older conjugation/form)\n感謝\tかんしゃ\tGratitude, thanks\n催す\tもよおす\tTo hold (an event), to organize\n熱意\tねつい\tEnthusiasm, zeal\n多數\tたすう\tLarge number, multitude\n特に\tとくに\tEspecially, particularly\n理事長\tりじちょう\tDirector, Chairman of the Board\n中將\tちゅうじょう\tLieutenant General\n長官\tちょうかん\tDirector, Chief, Head\n豫科\tよか\tPreparatory course\n士官學校\tしかんがっこう\tOfficer academy/school\n敎官\tきょうかん\tInstructor (esp. military or academic)\n少將\tしょうしょう\tMajor General\n臨席\tりんせき\tAttendance, presence (formal)\n宣誓\tせんせい\tOath, pledge, solemn vow\n\n\n---------------------------\n\n\n잡지명\t대동아 제14권 제5호\n발행일\t1942년 07월 01일\n기사제목\t川岸將軍等諸將星の前にて 東京留學生代表誓ふ, 帝都に於ける徵兵制祝賀の會\n기사형태\t논설\n\n川岸將軍等諸將星の前にて 東京留學生代表誓ふ, 帝都に於ける徵兵制祝賀の會\n徵兵制發表の先日, 東京に遊學中の半島靑年等が相集り感謝祝賀會を催したが, 當日は, 熱意に燃えた學生が多數集つた尙, 特に當日は\n朝鮮獎學會理事長  川岸中將\n浮虜情報局長官  上村中將\n陸軍豫科士官學校敎官部長  牧野少將, 長谷川少將\n等が臨席せられた. 左の一文は, 當日, 學生代表申君の熱熱なる宣誓である.\n\n我等は斯く誓ふ\n\n東京, 日本大學 申龍均\n 일본문-원문\n＜70-74＞",
    "magazine": "大東亞 第14巻 第5号",
